    <div class="body">
      <div class="quotetitle">Black Eagle wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">&quot;free from human error&quot; does not pass the laugh test.  Bitcoins may be free from certain kinds of human error, but their history has shown that there's still plenty of human error to go around.</div><br /><br />I'd say Bitcoin is actually more susceptible to errors simply because should an error in the hard-coded monetary policy become apparent, nothing can be done to fix it short of cashing out and starting over.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">scooby509 wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">“We have elected to put our money and faith in a mathematical framework that is free of politics and human error,” Tyler Winklevoss said.</div><br /><br />By stuffing it under your digital mattress?<br /><br />If they're worried about politics and human error, they're looking for a hedge. Gold, for example, will not gain value, but after transaction and storage costs, it won't lose it either.<br /><br />Bitcoins are a perfectly reasonable currency, that is, a device to transfer funds and enable commerce. Like any other currency, it's not an investment.<br /><br />So a handful of idiots are speculating on a billion dollar currency, and they are repeatedly making headlines in a $70 trillion-dollar world economy... why, exactly?</div><br /><br />They are not a perfectly reasonable currency. When exchanges regularly shut down, deflation is a <span style="font-style: italic">feature</span> rather than a bug, and small groups control a large volume of said currency and treat it as an investment <span style="font-style: italic">which means volatility and liquidity will only get worse</span>, you're not talking about a reasonable currency. You're talking about a currency backed by an economy in danger of imminent collapse.
      
    </div>
